SIMPLE: revolve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revolve
<hw>Re*volve"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Revolved</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Revolving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>revolvere</ets>, <ets>revolutum</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- +
<ets>volvere</ets> to roll, turn round. See <er>Voluble</er>, and cf.
<er>Revolt</er>, <er>revolution</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn or
roll round on, or as on, an axis, like a wheel; to rotate, -- which is
the more specific word in this sense.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the earth <qex>revolve</qex> thus, each house near the equator
must move a thousand miles an hour.</q> <rj><qau>I.
Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move in a curved path round a center; <as>as, the
planets <ex>revolve</ex> round the sun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pass in cycles; <as>as, the centuries
<ex>revolve</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To return; to pass.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revolve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Revolve
<hw>Re*volve"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to turn,
as on an axis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then in the east her turn she shines,⟦br⟧
<qex>Revolved</qex> on heaven's great axile.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to turn over and over in the mind; to reflect
repeatedly upon; to consider all aspects of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This having heard, straight I again <qex>revolved</qex>⟦br⟧
The law and prophets.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revolvement</ent>⟦br⟧
